The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring August 30 to September 5, 2009, as National Historically Black Colleges and Universities Week. The proclamation highlights the importance of education and the role of Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs) in providing opportunities and a solid education to generations of Americans. It acknowledges the contributions of HBCUs to the Civil Rights Movement, American history, and the African American middle class. The proclamation calls for celebrating the accomplishments of HBCUs and encourages them to employ innovative strategies to help students succeed in college and prepare for the global economy. It also calls upon public officials, educators, and the people of the United States to observe the week with appropriate programs and activities.